Proportional Odds Logit Modeling for Pacific Oyster Production Traits

Ernest O. Chuku

2023-07-31

Background

This R Markdown document outlines the steps for implementing proportional odds logit models POLM in R. Detailed analyses are provided to allow a comprehensive statistical examination of ordinal categorical outcomes. It includes sections on data requirements, fitting the POLM and model selection, estimating p-values and odds ratios, extracting goodness of fit parameters for the models, dealing with interaction terms, predicting cumulative probabilities and plotting stack column charts for the results, and predicting mean categorical outcomes for predictors.

Pacific oyster traits survey

The documentation uses data from a market survey of the Pacific oyster industry in Australia. The study targeted different stakeholders across two Australian territorial states, South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (TAS), and across supply chain segments, i.e., producers, producer-traders, and traders to gain insight into the important traits of the Pacific oyster for enhancing productivity ad marketability of the product. A four-part survey questionnaire was used to elicit responses from respondents from the PO industry. The questions were of mixed types although predominantly qualitative, including open-ended questions, raking of traits, Likert scale, and binary (Yes/No) type questions.

Various analytical approaches were applied to draw a comprehensive insight of the industry from the survey. However, this exercise focuses on the ranking and Likert-type questions. The response variables are assigned ranks or Likert scale categories. They are categorical and ordered. The researchers, therefore, identified proportional odds logistic regression as the appropriate statistical approach make the most meaning of the data. There are several approaches to handle ordered categorical outcomes (Agresti, 2002).

To demonstrate proportional odds logistic regression, we pick the example of a question that asked producers from the two Australian States to rank six traits of the Pacific oyster from 1st (most important) to 6th (least important) during production. The traits presented were fast growth (FG), uniform growth (UG), disease resistance (DR), high survival (HS), robustness in handling/processing (RH), and high tolerance to wide temperature variations (TT).

The procedure is replicated for the different datasets analysed with POLM in this Pacific oyster industry traits survey (Chuku et al.); Market traits Mktrait, colour Col, and shell shape Shp.

The outcome variable is ordinal. We, therefore, reorder the ranking levels from least to best. This is critical, and must be done!

df_Pdtrait$PdtraitRANK <- ordered(df_Pdtrait$PdtraitRANK,
  levels = c("6th", "5th", "4th", "3rd", "2nd", "1st"))
levels(df_Pdtrait$PdtraitRANK) # check the levels to confirm reordering
## [1] "6th" "5th" "4th" "3rd" "2nd" "1st"

Because the predictor variables are categorical, R generates dummy variables with base and indicator variables. Lets remind ourselves of how R handles dummy variables. R selects the first factor in alphabetical order as the base category, and the remaining categories as indicator variables. For Pdtrait, R selects the DR as the base, and for State R selects SA as the base.

Once the data structure is checked we are ready to apply proportional odds logit models

Fit the Proportional Odds Logistic Regression Models

The polr function from the MASS package is used for proportional odds regression.

We are interested to know the interaction effect of Pddtrait and State so we first go through a restricted modelling process. We compare three models to see which one is the best using likelihood ratios tests.

library(MASS)

POLR Model #1

fit001 <- polr(PdtraitRANK ~ Pdtrait,  
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Pdtrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

POLR Model #2

fit002 <- polr(PdtraitRANK ~ Pdtrait + State,  
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Pdtrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

POLR Model #3

fit003 <- polr(PdtraitRANK ~ Pdtrait + State + Pdtrait:State,  
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Pdtrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

Perform likelihood ratio tests of Models 1-3

anova(fit001, fit002, fit003)

There is marginal significance between Model 2 and 3, hence, we select Model #3 which has the interaction term.

Another model selection approach would be to specify the general model and conduct a stepwise backward and forward modelling. This is automated in R with the step function. Below, the step function also selects the model with interaction between Pdtrait and State as the best model. We are double sure about the selected model.

step(fit003, test = "Chisq", direction = "both") # perform a forward and backward stepwise model, and perform likelihood ratio test at each step

It is easier to interpret the model with p-values instead of the t-values. Calculate the p-values and append to the coefficients table

coefficients <- summary(fit003)$coefficients
# calculate p-values
p_value <- (1 - pnorm(abs(coefficients[ ,"t value"]), 0, 1))*2
# bind back to coefficients
(coefficients <- cbind(coefficients, p_value))

Odds ratios are very useful for explaining the parameter estimates. We calculate the odds ratios and further calculate a less biased version recommended for categorical predictors (Baker, 2006).

# calculate odds ratios
odds_ratio <- exp(coefficients[ ,"Value"]) #this is biased for categorical/dummy variables and tends to slightly overstate the effect
# for reduced bias odds ratios for dummy variables, use
odds_ratio_cat <- exp((coefficients[ ,"Value"])-((((coefficients[ ,"Std. Error"])^2)*(coefficients[ ,"Value"]))/2))
# combine with coefficient and p_value
(coefficients <- cbind(
  coefficients[ ,c("Value", "Std. Error", "p_value")],
  odds_ratio, odds_ratio_cat
))

Dealing with Interaction Term

The estimates for the interaction term in the model summary are tricky!! Needs a bit of extra work to explain them. To make life easier, because there is enough evidence of a significant State and Pdtrait interactions (at the 10% level), State and Pdtrait are bound to form a single categorical variable State|Pdtrait with 12 levels. One combination is selected as the reference level.

We concatenate the variables in the interaction term and refit the model. We go through all the procedures to include p-values, odds ratios, model fit parameters, etc.

Model #4 (with concateated iteraction term)

#concatenate string/factor variables and store as a new column
df_Pdtrait$stateTrait <- as.factor(paste(df_Pdtrait$State, df_Pdtrait$Pdtrait, sep = "|")) #combining State and Pdtrait 
# fit new model
fit004 <- polr(PdtraitRANK ~ stateTrait,
              Hess = TRUE, 
              data = df_Pdtrait,
              na.action = na.fail)

# get coefficients (it's in matrix form)
coefficients <- summary(fit004)$coefficients
# calculate p-values
p_value <- (1 - pnorm(abs(coefficients[ ,"t value"]), 0, 1))*2
# bind back to coefficients
coefficients <- cbind(coefficients, p_value)
# calculate odds ratios
odds_ratio <- exp(coefficients[ ,"Value"]) #this is biased for categorical/dummy variables and tends to slightly overstate the effect
# for reduced bias odds ratios for dummy variables, use
odds_ratio_cat <- exp((coefficients[ ,"Value"])-((((coefficients[ ,"Std. Error"])^2)*(coefficients[ ,"Value"]))/2))
# combine with coefficient and p_value
(coefficients <- cbind(
  coefficients[ ,c("Value", "Std. Error", "p_value")],
  odds_ratio, odds_ratio_cat
))

Multiple comparisons of model coefficients

library(emmeans)
#get estimated means coefficients of factor levels for a categorical predictor and store
em <- emmeans(fit004, "stateTrait")
#get multiple comparisons OR contrasts among the factor levels 
#contrast(em, "pairwise", adjust = "Tukey")
#save multiple comparisons as a dataframe
df_EstCOMP <- data.frame(contrast(em, "pairwise", adjust = "Tukey"), check.names = FALSE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
# calculate odds ratios
df_EstCOMP$OR <- round((exp(df_EstCOMP[ ,"estimate"])-1)*100)
# for reduced bias odds ratios for the differences in parameter estimates, use
df_EstCOMP$OR_cat <- round(((exp((df_EstCOMP[ ,"estimate"])-((((df_EstCOMP[ ,"SE"])^2)*(df_EstCOMP[ ,"estimate"]))/2)))-1)*100)
#reorder such that contrasts significant p-values will be on top
df_EstCOMP_ord <- df_EstCOMP[order(df_EstCOMP$p.value),] 
# View the reordered contrasts

Calculating specific odds for reverse differences that do not show above; REVERSE negative to positive (use absolute abs to convert negative estimate to positive)

#Subset data
df_EstCOMP_select <- df_EstCOMP %>% filter(contrast == "SA|HS - SA|UG") #reversing to "SA|UG - SA|HS"
# for reduced bias odds ratios for the differences in parameter estimates, use
ORcat <- exp((abs(df_EstCOMP_select$estimate))-((((df_EstCOMP_select$SE)^2)*(abs(df_EstCOMP_select$estimate)))/2))
# the bias-reduced odds; not appropriate for small odds ratios
Odds_cat <- (ORcat-1)*100

#for normal odds ratio
ORnorm <- exp((abs(df_EstCOMP_select$estimate)))
#Normal odds
Odds_norm <- (ORnorm-1)*100

Calculating specific odds for reverse differences that do not show above REVERSE positive to negative (multiply the estimate by -1 to negate it)

#Subset data
df_EstCOMP_select <- df_EstCOMP %>% filter(contrast == "TAS|HS - TAS|UG") 
#Reverse estimate positive to negative
REVestimate <- (-1)*(df_EstCOMP_select$estimate)
# for reduced bias odds ratios for the differences in parameter estimates, use
ORcat <- exp(REVestimate-((((df_EstCOMP_select$SE)^2)*(REVestimate))/2))

Predict mean categorical rank outcomes for specific traits of in each state

Now, instead of cumulative probablities of the ranking levels as demostrated above, we can predict the mean categorical outcomes using the best POLR model. For example we can use the model to generate the mean rank likely to be assigned the production trait, disease resistance by SA producers. Below is a demostration of how to do these predictions for all twelvee combinations of State*Pdtrait interactions.

# Get levels of each categorical predictor using the terms in the model
LEVELS1 <- levels(df_PdtraitRANKselect$Pdtrait)
LEVELS2 <- levels(df_PdtraitRANKselect$State)
# Create a data.frame to store the predictions
df_predRANKS <- data.frame(
  Pdtrait   = rep(LEVELS1, length(LEVELS2)),
  State = rep(LEVELS2, each=length(LEVELS1))
)
# Add the predictions
df_predRANKS$predRANKS <- predict(model_best, df_predRANKS)

# View the predicted ranks
df_predRANKS

Graphical Method [Manually Checking the proportional odds assumption (see detailed explanations at https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/dae/ordinal-logistic-regression/)]

library(Hmisc)

sf <- function(y) {
  c('Y>=1' = qlogis(mean(y >= 1)),
    'Y>=2' = qlogis(mean(y >= 2)),
    'Y>=3' = qlogis(mean(y >= 3)),
    'Y>=4' = qlogis(mean(y >= 4)),
    'Y>=5' = qlogis(mean(y >= 5)),
    'Y>=6' = qlogis(mean(y >= 6)))
}
